<body>
<p>
Let \(\{V_i\}_{i = 1}^n\) be a finite set of vector spaces.
</p>
<p>
A map 
\[\phi:\prod_{i = 1}^nV_i\to W\]
is <b>\(n\)-linear</b> if
\[
\begin{align*}
\phi(\alpha x_1 + \beta y_1, z_2,\dots,z_n)
&= \alpha\phi(x_1,z_2,\dots,z_n) + \beta\phi(y_1,z_2,\dots,z_n)\\
\phi(z_1, \alpha x_2 + \beta y_2,\dots,z_n)
&= \alpha\phi(z_1, x_2,\dots,z_n) + \beta\phi(z_1,y_2,\dots,z_n)\\
&\;\,\vdots\\
\phi(z_1,z_2,\dots,\alpha x_n + \beta y_n)
&= \alpha\phi(z_1, z_2,\dots,x_n) + \beta\phi(z_1,z_2,\dots,y_n)
\end{align*}
\]
i.e. if it is linear in every coordinate.
</p>
<p>
The free vector space
\(\mathbf F\left[\prod_{i=1}^nV_i\right],\)
which has basis \(\prod_{i=1}^nV_i\),
has a subspace \(R = \Span(X)\) where
\[X = \{
(\alpha x_1 + \beta y_1,z_2,\dots,z_n)
- \alpha(x_1,z_2,\dots,z_n) - \beta(y_1,z_2,\dots,z_n),\\
(z_1, \alpha x_2 + \beta y_2,\dots,z_n)
- \alpha(z_1,x_2,\dots,z_n) - \beta(z_1,y_2,\dots,z_n),\\
\dots,\\
(z_1,z_2,\dots, \alpha x_n + \beta y_n)
- \alpha(z_1,z_2,\dots,x_n) - \beta(z_1,z_2,\dots,y_n)
: \alpha, \beta\in\mathbf F,\;x_i,y_i,z_i\in V_i\}\]
</p>
<p>
The <b>tensor product</b> of the vector spaces \(V_1,\dots,V_n\)
is then the quotient space
\[\bigotimes_{i=1}^nV_i := \mathbf F\left[\prod_{i=1}^nV_i\right]\big/R.\]
</p>
<p>
Consider the map \(\tau:\prod_{i=1}^nV_i\to\bigotimes_{i=1}^nV_i\)
given by \((v_1,\dots,v_n)\mapsto(v_1,\dots,v_n) + R\).
</p>
<p>
We have that \(\tau\) is \(n\)-linear.
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
</details>
</p>
<p>
<i>The tensor product \(\bigotimes_{i=1}^nV_i\)
and its associated map \(\tau\)
have the following universal property:</i>
<br>
for any \(n\)-linear map \(\phi:\prod_{i = 1}^nV_i\to W\)
there exists a unique linear map \(\widetilde\phi:\bigotimes_{i=1}^nV_i\to W\)
such that \(\phi = \widetilde\phi\tau\).
<center>
<img width="250px" src="diagrams/tensor-product.svg">
</center>
</p>
<p>
Related: <a knowl="facts/vec/tensor">facts about the tensor product</a>.
</p>
